(829, 414, '_solution', '<p>Congratulations on taking your first step! Today\'s solution will showcase the simplicity and power of basic SQL. With just a few commands, you can easily access the data you are looking for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You\'ll start with the very basics of SQL using the <code>SELECT</code> and <code>FROM</code> queries. Think of them as your go-to tools for specifying which columns to display and which table to source data from.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n	email,\r\n	first_name,\r\n	last_name\r\nFROM [NextMobile Users]\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><code>SELECT:</code> Use this query to specify which columns you\'d like to see in your results.</li>\r\n	<li><code>FROM:</code> This query points to the table from which you want to pull the data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n  â¡ï¸ Query Result: 943 <strong>rows</strong>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\nGreat job! By using only two simple commands, you have successfully accessed user data stored in the database. As we continue, you will uncover the countless possibilities that SQL has to offer. Get prepared for Day 2!'),
