INSERT INTO `wp_postmeta` (`meta_id`, `post_id`, `meta_key`, `meta_value`) VALUES
(1674, 665, '_solution', '<p>Today\'s challenge in SQL focuses on numerical calculations and comparisons. Leverage the <code class=\"fw-bold\">*</code> (multiplication) operator as you perform arithmetic operations and analyze data with precision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this challenge, you\'ll also use the <code class=\"fw-bold\">>=</code> (greater than or equal to) operator. This important operator allows you to filter your results, capturing data that meets or potentially exceeds a specified threshold.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id, \r\n    points * 1.5 AS bonus_points\r\nFROM [NextMobile Loyalty]\r\nWHERE \r\n    points * 1.5 >= 150000\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Specifies which columns should appear in the output of the query. Here, it\'s used to display the ID and their bonus points after conversion.</li>\r\n    <li><code>*</code>: The arithmetic operator multiplies the \'points\' by 1.5 to calculate the bonus points each customer will receive.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Identifies the source table from which to retrieve the data. In this case, it\'s pulling from the \'NextMobile Loyalty\' table.</li>\r\n    <li><code  class=\"fw-bold\">WHERE</code>: Use conditions to filter specific data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>>=</code>: The comparison operator used here ensures that only customers whose bonus points are greater than or equal to 150,000 are selected.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    â¡ï¸ Query Result: <strong>259</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>You have successfully tackled a challenge that combines arithmetic with data analysis. This skill is extremely valuable in the marketing world. Day 5 awaits with more insights and intrigue!</p>\r\n'),
