(1693, 666, '_solution', '<p>Let\'s explore the art of selection! Today, you will learn how to combine conditions to create more complex, yet specific queries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For today, embark on a journey to learn about the power of exclusivity with the <code>=</code> operator. Furthermore, the <code>OR</code> function will introduce you to setting multiple conditions in a single query.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id, \r\n    email, \r\n    mobility,\r\n    internet\r\nFROM [NextMobile Services]\r\nWHERE \r\n    mobility = \'Essential 120\' OR internet = \'Fibe 500\'\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Choose the columns for the output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Specify the table containing the data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Define conditions to refine the results.</li>\r\n    <li><code>=</code>: The equal operator is used to compare two values, columns, or expressions. It checks whether the left side is exactly the same as the right side and returns true if they are equal.</li>\r\n    <li><code>OR</code>: A logical operator that lets the query match any of the given conditions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    â¡ï¸ Query Result: <strong>463</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Today, you learned how to combine multiple conditions in SQL to identify customers who may be eligible for upgrades. Get ready for more challenges as SQL30 continues!</p>\r\n'),
