(1751, 670, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 8! In today\'s challenge, you will use the <code>IN</code> operator to filter data based on a list of values. This will make your SQL queries cleaner and more efficient. So, let\'s explore and see how this data filtering works in real life!</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id,\r\n    data_plan\r\nFROM [NextMobile Plans]\r\nWHERE\r\n    data_plan IN (\'Flex\', \'Flex Plus\', \'Essential\')\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Define the columns for your output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Indicate the table where the data resides.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Establish conditions to filter the data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>IN</code>: A handy operator that allows you to specify multiple values in a <code>WHERE</code> clause. The IN operator is similar to using = with OR operators. For example: A = 1 OR A = 2 OR ...</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    â¡ Query Result: <strong>436</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>The <code>IN</code> operator simplifies your queries and saves time by allowing you to write fewer lines of SQL code. In the upcoming challenges, you will encounter more scenarios where the <code>IN</code> operator will be useful in solving them.</p>'),
