(1809, 673, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 11! Today\'s task involves retrieving data using the <code>TOP</code> and <code>WHERE</code> clauses. Your goal is to identify customers who have spent over $2,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    TOP 50\r\n    id,\r\n    amount\r\nFROM [NextMobile Spend]\r\nWHERE\r\n    amount > 2000\r\nORDER BY amount DESC\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT TOP 50</code>: This command selects the first 50 records from the result set. It\'s useful when you need a limited number of records from a large dataset.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Points to the source table for the query.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Filters the records to include only those records where the <code>amount</code> column value is greater than 2000.</li>\r\n    <li><code>ORDER BY amount DESC</code>: This part of the query sorts the results by the <code>amount</code> column in descending order (<code>DESC</code>). This means the customers with the highest spend amounts are listed first.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    â¡ Query Result: <strong>50</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Great job! Today, you used SQL to identify NextMobile\'s top-notch customers, a crucial step in finding a targeted segment quickly. Each SQL challenge you overcome provides you with a fresh perspective. Stay tuned for more rewarding tasks in the upcoming days!</p>\r\n'),
