(1896, 681, '_solution', '<p>As you work with more complex datasets, there will be times when you need to group similar entities together. This can be based on categories, time periods, or any other shared attribute. The <code>GROUP BY</code> clause allows you to accomplish this, creating meaningful segments in your data. But that\'s not all! With the <code>HAVING</code> clause, you can filter these groups based on aggregated conditions, further refining your insights.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    state, \r\n	COUNT(id)\r\nFROM [NextMobile Users]\r\nGROUP BY \r\n    state\r\nHAVING COUNT(id) > 50\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Pick out columns or aggregate functions for output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Point to the relevant table.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GROUP BY</code>: Aggregate data by specified columns.</li>\r\n    <li><code>HAVING</code>: Filter the results of your aggregation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ð¡ <strong>Query Result:</strong> state, count\r\n	<ul class=\"mb-0\">\r\n		<li>CA, 332</li>\r\n		<li>FL, 276</li>\r\n		<li>NY, 169</li>\r\n		<li>AZ, 91</li>\r\n		<li>WA, 57</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>By analyzing the geographic distribution of your users, you have laid the foundation for better segmentation. Your expertise in SQL is strategically helping you group rows in your dataset. Keep up the good work!</p>\r\n'),
