(2046, 705, '_solution', '<p>On Day 17, your focus is to identify recently launched accounts for a new promotional campaign. Date functions are useful for querying data based on existing values in a table. Today\'s challenge involves using the <code>DATEADD</code> function to calculate the date 90 days ago from today. <code>DATEADD</code> is a useful function for querying databases based on future and past dates, referencing existing data in your data extension or table.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT id, launch_date\r\nFROM [NextMobile Users]\r\nWHERE launch_date &gt;= DATEADD(DAY, -90, GETDATE()) \r\nAND launch_date &lt; GETDATE()\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Retrieves specified columns, in this case, user IDs and their launch dates.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Designates the table where user data is stored.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Filters results based on a condition.</li>\r\n    <li><code>DATEADD(DAY, -90, GETDATE())</code>: Calculates the date 90 days ago from today, setting the starting point for identifying new accounts.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GETDATE()</code>: Retrieves the current date to ensure we\'re considering the most recent 90-day period.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ð¡ <strong>Query Result:</strong> 17 (as of 2024-02-22)\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Well done! By effectively using SQL\'s date functions, you\'ve successfully identified the newest members of the NextMobile community. This allows us to provide these new users with tailored promotions, helping to establish a strong initial relationship. Keep improving your SQL skills as they\'re vital for creating efficient and timely marketing strategies!</p>\r\n'),
