(2122, 709, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to the solution walkthrough for Day 21! NextMobile\'s latest campaign is based on data-driven decisions. Today, you\'ll use the <code>INNER JOIN</code> function to merge rows from our user and usage datasets using the shared <code>id</code> column. This introduces you to SQL\'s relational database capabilities, an essential skill for any data professional.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    s.state, \r\n    AVG(u.data_usage) AS average_data_usage\r\nFROM \r\n    [NextMobile Users] AS s\r\nINNER JOIN \r\n    [NextMobile Usage] AS u ON s.id = u.id\r\nGROUP BY \r\n    s.state\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Initiates the selection of specific columns for output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>AVG</code>: Calculates the average data usage for users in each state.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM [NextMobile Users] AS s</code>: Specifies the first dataset to pull data from, assigning it an alias for easy reference.</li>\r\n    <li><code>INNER JOIN [NextMobile Usage] AS u</code>: Indicates the second dataset to join with the first, using an alias for clarity.</li>\r\n    <li><code>ON s.id = u.id</code>: Defines the common attribute between the datasets that SQL uses to join the data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GROUP BY s.state</code>: Groups the results by state, which is necessary for the <code>AVG</code> function to calculate the average per state.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ð¡ <strong>Query Result</strong>\r\n    <table class=\"table\">\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <th>State</th>\r\n            <th>Average Data Usage</th>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>WA</td>\r\n            <td>37.79</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>NY</td>\r\n            <td>34.31</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>CA</td>\r\n            <td>35.25</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>OR</td>\r\n            <td>41.40</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>FL</td>\r\n            <td>36.00</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>AZ</td>\r\n            <td>35.43</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </table>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>You just took a huge leap in SQL! Linking tables opens a whole new world of data insights. Now, no matter how spread out the information is, you have the tools to bring it together. Get ready â more multi-table challenges await!</p>\r\n'),
