(2297, 719, '_solution', '<p>In today\'s task, you will create an SQL query to explore data from NextMobile\'s Marketing Cloud. By examining email sends, clicks, and bounces, you will determine state-specific CTRs. This will enable the marketing team to refine their email strategy for improved outcomes.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT\r\n    u.state,\r\n    (SUM(CASE WHEN c.IsUnique = 1 THEN 1.0 ELSE 0 END) / (COUNT(s.SubscriberKey) - SUM(CASE WHEN b.IsUnique = 1 THEN 1.0 ELSE 0 END))) * 100 AS ctr\r\nFROM\r\n    [NextMobile Users] u\r\nJOIN \r\n    [NextMobile Sent_2023] s \r\nON\r\n    u.id = s.SubscriberKey\r\nLEFT JOIN\r\n    [NextMobile Click_2023] c\r\nON\r\n    s.SubscriberKey = c.SubscriberKey AND s.JobId = c.JobId\r\nLEFT JOIN\r\n    [NextMobile Bounce_2023] b\r\nON\r\n    s.SubscriberKey = b.SubscriberKey AND s.JobId = b.JobId    \r\nWHERE\r\n    s.EventDate >= \'2023-01-01\' \r\n    AND s.EventDate <= \'2023-12-31\' \r\nGROUP BY\r\n    u.state\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Specifies the columns to be included in the output, including the state of the subscriber and the calculated click-through rate (CTR).</li>\r\n    <li><code>SUM</code>: Aggregates the total number of unique clicks and bounces for each state.</li>\r\n    <li><code>CASE</code>: Performs conditional logic to calculate the number of unique clicks and bounces for each subscriber.</li>\r\n    <li><code>COUNT</code>: Counts the total number of subscribers who received emails.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Identifies the data sources used in the query, including the NextMobile Users, NextMobile Sent_2023, NextMobile Click_2023, and NextMobile Bounce_2023 data views.</li>\r\n    <li><code>JOIN</code>: Combines data from different tables based on common keys, such as the subscriber key and job ID, ensuring that relevant information from each table is included in the analysis.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GROUP BY</code>: Groups the results by the state of the subscribers, allowing for the calculation of the CTR for each state separately.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Filters the sent email data to include only those records with event dates falling within the specified range (January 1, 2023, to December 31, 2023).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ð¡ <strong>Query Result</strong>\r\n    <table class=\"table\">\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <th>state</th>\r\n            <th>ctr</th>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>WA</td>\r\n            <td>15.99</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>NY</td>\r\n            <td>16.38</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>CA</td>\r\n            <td>15.99</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>OR</td>\r\n            <td>12.06</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>FL</td>\r\n            <td>16.44</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>AZ</td>\r\n            <td>16.62</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </table>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>With this final CTR analysis, you have completed the entire SQL30 challenge! Your dedication has provided you with potent data analysis skills, preparing you to understand and run complex SQL queries. Look out for an email soon, as we will be sending instructions on how to claim your well-deserved certification and a short feedback survey.</p>'),
